`GET /users` returns names and email addresses to any unauthenticated caller. Even in a demo, this is the #1 OWASP category and sets a bad default.

**Fix — require an authenticated principal before returning user data:**
```js
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const header = req.headers.authorization || '';
  const token = header.startsWith('Bearer ') ? header.slice(7) : null;
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'unauthorized' });
  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET, { algorithms: ['HS256'] });
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'invalid_token' });
  }
}

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => { /* ... */ });
```

Also consider minimizing the response (don't return `email` unless the caller is authorized to see it — principle of least privilege / data minimization).

---

### 2. A05 — Security Misconfiguration: no security headers (High)

No `helmet`, so responses are missing `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `Content-Security-Policy`, `X-Frame-Options`, `Referrer-Policy`, and Express's default `X-Powered-By: Express` header leaks the framework.

**Fix:**
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet({
  contentSecurityPolicy: { useDefaults: true },
  hsts: { maxAge: 31536000, includeSubDomains: true, preload: true },
  referrerPolicy: { policy: 'no-referrer' },
}));
```

---

### 3. A05 — No CORS policy (Medium)

With no `cors` middleware, Express relies on browser defaults. If you intend this to be a browser-facing API, you need an explicit allowlist; if you don't, you should explicitly reject cross-origin requests.

**Fix (allowlist):**
```js
const cors = require('cors');
const allowed = (process.env.CORS_ORIGINS || '').split(',').filter(Boolean);
app.use(cors({
  origin: (origin, cb) => (!origin || allowed.includes(origin)) ? cb(null, true) : cb(new Error('CORS')),
  methods: ['GET'],
  credentials: false,
}));
```

---

### 4. A04 — Insecure Design: no rate limiting / DoS protection (Medium)

A single unauthenticated endpoint with no rate limiting is trivially abusable (scraping, credential stuffing on any future auth endpoint, resource exhaustion).

**Fix:**
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 60, standardHeaders: true, legacyHeaders: false }));
```

---

### 5. A05 — No request body / payload limits (Medium)

If/when you add `app.use(express.json())`, it defaults to a 100 KB limit which is often too large, and in older setups can be unlimited. Always set it explicitly and add a global timeout.

**Fix:**
```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' }));
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false, limit: '10kb' }));
```

Also set server timeouts to resist slowloris-style attacks:
```js
const server = app.listen(port, () => { /* ... */ });
server.headersTimeout = 10_000;
server.requestTimeout = 15_000;
server.keepAliveTimeout = 5_000;
```

---

### 6. A09 — Logging & Monitoring failures (Medium)

`console.log` is the only logging. There is no request log, no error log, no correlation ID, no structured output. A compromised or misbehaving service will be invisible.

**Fix — structured logger + request IDs:**
```js
const pino = require('pino');
const pinoHttp = require('pino-http');
const logger = pino({ redact: ['req.headers.authorization', 'req.headers.cookie'] });
app.use(pinoHttp({ logger, genReqId: (req) => req.headers['x-request-id'] || crypto.randomUUID() }));
```

---

### 7. A05 — No error-handling middleware; stack traces could leak (Medium)

Any thrown error currently falls through to Express's default handler, which in development mode leaks stack traces. You should register a terminal error handler and never echo error internals to clients.

**Fix:**
```js
